reason.tex:
%text As a first step, we should take stock of the facts that have been given to us.
Hence, if events are defined as follows, % \begin{tabular}{|c|c|} \hline \text{Event} & \text{Meaning} \\ \hline A & \text{A speaks the truth} \\ \hline B & \text{B speaks the truth} \\ \hline C & \text{A and B contradict} \\ \hline \end{tabular} %text
then it follows that % \begin{align} P(A) &= 0.6 \implies P(\bar{A}) = 1-0.6 = 0.4 \\ P(B) &= 0.9\implies P(\bar{B}) = 1-0.9 = 0.1 \end{align}

options.tex:
\begin{align}
C &= (A\cap\bar{B})\cup (\bar{A}\cap B) \\
P(C) &= P(A)\cdot P(\bar{B}) + P(\bar{A})\cdot P(B) \\ 
&= 0.6\times 0.1 + 0.4\times 0.9 = 0.42 \\
&\implies \text{ in 42\% of the cases}
\end{align}

\begin{align}
C &= (\bar{A}\cap\bar{B})\cup (\bar{A}\cap B) \\
P(C) &= P(\bar{A})\cdot P(\bar{B}) + P(\bar{A})\cdot P(B) \\ 
&= 0.4\times 0.1 + 0.4\times 0.9 = 0.4 \\
&\implies \text{ in 40\% of the cases}
\end{align}

reason.tex:
%text If $A$ and $B$ both lie, then there is no contradiction.
If $A$ and $B$ both speak the truth, then also there is no contradiction.
Only when one lies and the other speaks the truth is there a contradiction. Hence, the event $C$ is % \begin{align} C &= \underbrace{(A\cap\bar{B})}_{\text{B lies, A does not}} \cup \underbrace{(\bar{A}\cap B)}_{\text{A lies, B does not}} \\ P(C) &= P(A)\cdot P(\bar{B}) + P(\bar{A})\cdot P(B) \\ &= 0.6\times 0.1 + 0.4\times 0.9 = 0.42 \\ &\implies \text{ in 42\% of the cases} \end{align}

options.tex:
\begin{align}
P(C\vert B) &= P(\bar{A}) \\ 
P(C\vert A) &= P(\bar{B})
\end{align}
